21 SECTION 4.(c) G.S. 113-229(n)(3) reads as rewritten:
22 "(3) "Marshland" means any salt marsh or other marsh subject to regular or
23 occasional flooding by tides, including wind tides (whether or not the
24 tidewaters reach the marshland areas through natural or artificial
25 watercourses), provided this shall not include hurricane or tropical storm tides.
26 Salt marshland or other marsh shall be those areas upon which grow some,
27 but not necessarily all, of the following salt marsh and marsh plant species:
28 Smooth or salt water Cordgrass (Spartina alterniflora), Black Needlerush
29 (Juncus roemerianus), Glasswort (Salicornia spp.), Salt Grass (Distichlis
30 spicata), Sea Lavender (Limonium spp.), Bulrush (Scirpus spp.), Saw Grass
31 (Cladium jamaicense), Cattail (Typha spp.), Salt-Meadow Grass(Spartina
32 patens), and Salt Reed-Grass (Spartina cynosuroides). A marshland shall not
33 include any area contained within a man-made ditch as defined under
34 G.S. 113A-103(8a)."
35 SECTION 5.(a) Article 7 of Chapter 113A of the General Statutes is amended by
36 adding a new Part to read:
37 "Part 5A. Upland Basin Marinas.
38 "§ 113A-129.10. Legislative findings; broad construction.
39 (a) The General Assembly finds that development of properly sited and planned upland
40 basin marinas to accommodate vessels promotes the public welfare for a number of reasons,
41 including all of the following:
42 (1) Increasing riparian property owner access to the State's public trust waters.
43 (2) Expanding the total area of the State's public trust waters.
44 (3) Reducing and confining potential storm debris.
45 (4) Reducing the need for additional onshore impervious surfaces associated with
46 parking.
47 (5) Promoting the use of innovative technologies.
48 (6) Promoting the collection of site-specific data designed to assure compliance
49 with applicable water quality standards.
50 (7) Maintaining or improving overall water quality when sited, designed,
51 constructed, and operated in conformance with the provisions of this Part.
House Bill 352-Fourth Edition Page 9

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) Accordingly, it is the intent of the General Assembly that this Part be broadly
2 construed to further the general purposes stated in this Part.
3 "§ 113A-129.11. Definitions.
4 As used in this Part, the following definitions apply:
5 (1) AEC or Area of Environmental Concern. – An area designated by the Coastal
6 Resources Commission pursuant to G.S. 113A-113.
7 (2) Boat slip. – Any structure adjoining, attached to, or part of a pier which has
8 the capacity to store one boat.
9 (3) Upland basin marina. – A marina constructed by excavating or dredging lands
10 of elevations above the current mean or ordinary high-water mark and
11 designed to accommodate more than 10 vessels or boat slips. Upland basin
12 marinas shall be considered a water dependent use for purposes of general use
13 standards adopted by the Coastal Resources Commission.
14 "§ 113A-129.12. Upland basin marina permitting and development.
15 (a) Unless the Director of the Division of Water Resources or the Director of the Division
16 of Coastal Management makes a finding, based on site-specific technical information, that the
17 applicant cannot comply with one or more of the criteria listed in subsection (b) of this section,
18 the Division of Water Resources and the Division of Coastal Management shall approve an
19 application for the development of an upland basin marina project, within 60 days after the
20 applicant submits a completed application or supplemental information requested by the
21 Department to demonstrate compliance with all of the criteria set forth in subsection (b) of this
22 section. The Department may make one written request for any supplemental information
23 necessary to make its finding within 30 days after the applicant submits a complete application,
24 and the permit may be conditioned upon measures that are necessary to ensure that the applicant
25 complies with all of the criteria set forth in subsection (b) of this section. When the Department
26 requests supplemental information, the 60-day review period restarts upon receipt of the
27 supplemental information requested by the Department. If the Department fails to act on an
28 application for the development of an upland basin marina project within the 60-day review period,
29 the application shall be deemed approved.
30 (b) The criteria with which an upland basin marina shall comply to qualify for permitting
31 pursuant to subsection (a) of this section are all of the following:
32 (1) The upland basin marina is designed to accommodate 10 or more vessels,
33 including individual homeowner boat slips, boat lifts, or dry stack storage.
34 (2) The waters contained in the upland basin marina have a dissolved oxygen
35 content equal to or greater than the dissolved oxygen content of the water
36 located 50 feet plus or minus 5 feet from the entrance to the upland basin
37 marina before development. As part of the application, an applicant shall
38 provide to the Division of Water Resources and the Division of Coastal
39 Management site-specific sampling data documenting pre-project dissolved
40 oxygen levels of the water located 50 feet plus or minus 5 feet from each
41 proposed entrance to the proposed upland basin marina. Waters located within
42 the upland basin marina shall be classified the same as the waters in the
43 immediate vicinity of any entrance to the upland basin marina.
44 (3) The project has a bond or set-aside funds for the long-term operation and
45 maintenance of any technology required to meet or exceed then-applicable
46 water quality standards. The applicant shall provide an estimate of annual
47 operation and maintenance costs and the bond or set-aside funds shall be equal
48 to five years of the estimated annual operation and maintenance costs.
49 (4) Construction of the upland basin marina impacts or removes a total area of
50 coastal wetlands that is no more than five percent (5%) of the total area of the
51 proposed upland basin marina waters.
Page 10 House Bill 352-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (5) Construction of the upland basin marina impacts or removes a total linear
2 footage of coastal wetlands fringe that is no more than ten percent (10%) of
3 the total linear footage of existing coastal wetlands along the shoreline of the
4 property or properties of the permit applicant.
5 (6) The proposed upland basin marina project complies with specific use
6 standards adopted by the Coastal Resources Commission for navigation
7 channels, canals, and boat basins. An upland basin marina project shall not be
8 considered a "finger canal" or "finger canal system" if the project does not
9 contain right angle corners.
10 (7) The upland basin marina has a 30-foot vegetated buffer or buffers along the
11 post-project shoreline, excluding any newly created inside shorelines, if
12 required by the Department.
13 (8) The proposed upland basin marina project complies with specific use
14 standards adopted by the Coastal Resources Commission for marinas, except
15 that a stormwater management system may be located within the 30-foot
16 buffer area described in subdivision (7) of this subsection.
17 (9) The project includes mitigation or has mitigation credits for wetland impacts
18 caused by excavation or construction of entrances, exits, and upland vessel
19 accommodation areas, where such entrances, exits, and upland vessel
20 accommodation areas exceed 125 linear feet of shoreline in total.
21 (10) The upland basin marina is sited and designed to avoid significant adverse
22 impacts to the productivity and biologic integrity of coastal wetlands, shellfish
23 beds, submerged aquatic vegetation, water quality, and spawning and primary
24 nursery areas. Compliance with subdivisions (1) through (10) of this
25 subsection shall create a presumption that the project has avoided significant
26 adverse impacts to the productivity and biologic integrity of coastal wetlands,
27 non-coastal wetlands, shellfish beds, submerged aquatic vegetation, water
28 quality, spawning areas, and primary nursery areas and to have complied with
29 State water quality antidegradation requirements. Compliance constitutes
30 appropriate avoidance of significant adverse environmental impacts,
31 including those identified in this Part.
32 (c) The submission of a Major Development Coastal Area Management Act (CAMA)
33 permit application for an upland basin marina project shall constitute a complete application for
34 purposes of water quality certification review by the Division of Water Resources. Unless the
35 Director of the Division of Water Resources or the Director of the Division of Coastal
36 Management objects in writing or requests additional information necessary to evaluate
37 compliance with water quality standards as provided in subsection (a) of this section, no further
38 information shall be required by the Department for purposes of evaluating whether the upland
39 basin marina project will comply with water quality standards or CAMA use standards referenced
40 in this Part. Compliance with the Major Development CAMA permitting process shall also
41 constitute compliance with all relevant provisions of Article 1 of this Chapter.
42 (d) The Department shall allow an applicant for an upland basin marina project to use
43 innovative technology to maintain dissolved oxygen levels or improve dissolved oxygen above
44 pre-project ambient dissolved oxygen levels in the immediate vicinity of the entrance to the
45 upland basin marina. If the applicant proposes the use of innovative technology, the Department
46 shall require the permit holder to provide financial assurance, in the form of a bond or set-aside
47 funds, for long-term operation and maintenance of the innovative technology, in accordance with
48 subdivision (b)(3) of this section. If the applicant provides a certification from a North Carolina
49 licensed professional engineer that the proposed innovative technology is capable of attaining
50 required dissolved oxygen levels within the proposed upland basin marina, the Department shall
51 not require any additional information.
House Bill 352-Fourth Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (e) In the absence of site-specific technical concerns provided to the applicant by the
2 Director of the Division of Water Resources or the Director of the Division of Coastal
3 Management based on information provided during the permit review process, an upland basin
4 marina project that satisfies the criteria provided in subsection (b) of this section shall be deemed
5 to satisfy all of the following:
6 (1) CAMA management objectives and relevant use standards of the estuarine
7 and ocean system AECs.
8 (2) CAMA management objectives and use standards of the coastal wetlands
9 AEC.
10 (3) The policy goals stated in G.S. 113-102(b).
11 (f) Nothing in this section shall be construed to abrogate the Department's authority to
12 ensure long-term compliance with applicable water quality standards in light of the goals and
13 requirements set forth in this Part. If data collected as part of the requirements of this Part, or
14 otherwise, indicate noncompliance with applicable water quality standards in the waters within
15 the upland basin marina or adjacent waters within the vicinity of each entrance to the upland
16 basin marina, the Department may require the owner of the upland basin marina development at
17 the time of the noncompliance to bring the waters within the upland basin marina and adjacent
18 waters into compliance with applicable water quality standards, in light of the overall goals and
19 policies set forth in this Part to promote the construction and use of upland basin marinas.
20 (g) Nothing in this section shall obviate the need for an applicant to obtain all relevant
21 federal permits required for the upland basin marina project."
22 SECTION 5.(b) G.S. 143-214.1A reads as rewritten:
23 "§ 143-214.1A. Water quality certification requirements for certain projects.
24 (a) The following requirements shall govern applications for certification filed with the
25 Department pursuant to section 401 of the Clean Water Act, 33 U.S.C. § 1341(a)(1), for (i)
26 maintenance dredging projects partially funded by the Shallow Draft Navigation Channel
27 Dredging and Aquatic Weed Fund and Fund, (ii) projects involving the distribution or
28 transmission of energy or fuel, including natural gas, diesel, petroleum, or electricity:electricity,
29 and (iii) projects involving construction of an upland basin marina, as defined in
30 G.S. 113A-129.11:
31 …."
32 SECTION 5.(c) Subsection (b) of this section is effective when it becomes law and
33 applies to applications for section 401 certification pending or submitted on or after that date.
34 SECTION 6. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
35 law.
